-\paragraph{Data Loss Prevention (DLP).} DLP systems~\cite{dlp_survey} detect policy violations in data flows using content inspection (regular expressions, ML classifiers, fingerprinting). Modern enterprise DLP (e.g., Microsoft Purview, Zscaler) has added contextual signals such as user role and endpoint location. However, DLP operates on content and network metadata — it does not understand agent session state, multi-turn data accumulation, or entity-relationship knowledge (e.g., that a contact is inactive, or that a directory-local file has an HR-only audience policy). The violations in PhantomPolicy that involve accumulated session leakage, context boundaries, and audience restrictions cannot be detected by content inspection alone. Sentinel's world-state reasoning is complementary to DLP; the ContentLeakageVerifier component provides DLP-style text fingerprinting as one of five verifiers.
-
-To quantify this coverage gap: of PhantomPolicy's 12 violation cases, only 3 — the two \emph{text-output leakage} cases where confidential figures appear verbatim in the outbound email body, plus one context-boundary case carrying quoted pricing data — are in principle detectable by content pattern matching. The remaining 9 violations involve no sensitive strings in the outbound content: they are structural violations that require knowing a file's audience policy (HR\_ONLY), the accumulated taint of a session's data sources, or the relationship between a document and its intended recipients. A DLP-only approach therefore achieves at most 25\% recall (3/12) on this benchmark; the detection gap is architectural, not a matter of classifier quality. Our contribution is not a new policy type or enforcement mechanism, but a new failure mode: contextual violations that are invisible to model-only judgment when policy-relevant world state is not explicitly surfaced into the decision pathway.
-
-\paragraph{LLM safety and alignment.} Safety-trained models~\cite{rlhf, cai} are designed to refuse harmful or ethically problematic requests. Our work addresses a different problem: the model is not being asked to do anything harmful from its perspective. Fine-tuning approaches that teach models to enforce specific organizational policies are brittle (policies change, organizations differ) and cannot cover the open-ended space of organizational world states.
-
-\paragraph{Prompt injection and adversarial attacks.} A growing body of work addresses adversarial manipulation of LLM-based agents~\cite{promptinjection}. Policy-invisible violations require no adversary: the user is cooperative and the request is legitimate. The threat model is fundamentally different.
+\paragraph{Data Loss Prevention (DLP).} DLP systems~\cite{dlp_survey} detect policy violations in data flows using content inspection (regular expressions, ML classifiers, fingerprinting). Modern enterprise DLP (e.g., Microsoft Purview, Zscaler) has added contextual signals such as user role and endpoint location. However, DLP operates on content and network metadata — it does not understand agent session state, multi-turn data accumulation, or entity-relationship knowledge (e.g., that a contact is inactive, or that a directory-local file has an HR-only audience policy). As quantified in \S\ref{sec:simpler}, a content-only approach achieves at most 25\% recall on PhantomPolicy; the gap is architectural, not a matter of classifier quality.
 
-\paragraph{LLM-based agents and tool use.} Recent work has explored agents that use tools via ReAct-style loops~\cite{react} or learned tool use~\cite{toolformer}. Comprehensive benchmarking efforts such as AgentBench~\cite{liu2024agentbench} evaluate LLMs across diverse agentic tasks but focus on task completion rather than policy compliance. Agent safety work has primarily addressed risks from executing dangerous actions (code execution, shell access, irreversible operations)~\cite{ruan2024identifying}, with R-Judge~\cite{yuan2024rjudge} benchmarking safety risk awareness and AgentHarm~\cite{andriushchenko2024agentharm} measuring harmfulness of adversarially prompted agents. AgentDojo~\cite{debenedetti2024agentdojo} provides a dynamic environment for evaluating attacks and defenses. Our focus is orthogonal to these efforts: policy violations in routine, authorized operations (send email, share file) that are dangerous only in specific organizational contexts — no adversary is required. Recent work on safe agentic deployment~\cite{mo2024trembling} addresses the need for guarantees in agentic systems but focuses on avoiding catastrophic actions rather than detecting contextual policy violations. Guardrail systems such as NeMo Guardrails~\cite{rebedea2023nemo} and Llama Guard~\cite{inan2023llama} provide input/output filtering based on content categories, but do not incorporate organizational world-state for policy verification.
+\paragraph{LLM safety, alignment, and adversarial attacks.} Safety-trained models~\cite{rlhf, cai} refuse harmful requests; our work addresses a different problem where the action is not harmful from the model's perspective. Prompt injection research~\cite{promptinjection} addresses adversarial manipulation of agents; policy-invisible violations require no adversary — the user is cooperative and the request is legitimate.
 
-\paragraph{Access control and RBAC.} Role-based access control~\cite{rbac} enforces \emph{authorization} — what a principal is permitted to do. Policy-invisible violations involve authorized principals performing authorized actions that nonetheless violate contextual policy. RBAC has no mechanism for audience-based restrictions, session context tracking, or temporal validity checking of external contacts.
+\paragraph{Agent safety and tool use.} Agent safety work has primarily addressed risks from executing dangerous actions~\cite{ruan2024identifying}, with R-Judge~\cite{yuan2024rjudge} benchmarking safety risk awareness and AgentHarm~\cite{andriushchenko2024agentharm} measuring harmfulness of adversarially prompted agents. AgentDojo~\cite{debenedetti2024agentdojo} evaluates prompt injection attacks and defenses. Mo et al.~\cite{mo2024trembling} address guarantees for agentic systems but focus on avoiding catastrophic actions. Our focus is orthogonal: policy violations in routine, authorized operations that are dangerous only in specific organizational contexts.
 
-\paragraph{Information Flow Control (IFC).} IFC~\cite{sabelfeld2003language} is a program analysis discipline that tracks how sensitive data flows through a system and enforces policies such as non-interference. The Decentralized Label Model~\cite{myers1997decentralized} provides a formal framework for attaching sensitivity labels to data and verifying that high-confidentiality data does not flow to low-confidentiality principals. Our accumulated session leakage and context boundary categories are conceptually related to IFC: reading a CONFIDENTIAL document ``taints'' the session, and subsequent outbound actions must respect that taint. However, IFC operates at the program analysis level (type systems, runtime monitors on code), not at the level of agent tool calls and organizational policy graphs. Extending IFC principles to LLM agent contexts is a natural direction for future work.
+\paragraph{Access control and information flow.} Role-based access control~\cite{rbac} enforces authorization — what a principal is permitted to do — but has no mechanism for audience-based restrictions or session context tracking. Information flow control~\cite{sabelfeld2003language} tracks data sensitivity through programs; our accumulated session leakage and context boundary categories are conceptually related (reading a CONFIDENTIAL document ``taints'' the session), but IFC operates at the program analysis level, not at the level of agent tool calls and organizational policy graphs.
 
-\paragraph{Runtime verification and policy engines.} Runtime verification~\cite{leucker2009brief} monitors system executions against formal specifications at runtime. Policy engines such as Open Policy Agent (OPA)~\cite{opa} and AWS Cedar evaluate authorization queries against declarative policies. Sentinel is closest in spirit to a runtime policy engine applied to agent tool calls, with the distinction that it uses a world model with organizational entity relationships rather than purely attribute-based policies. Integrating Sentinel-style world-state verification with established policy engine infrastructure is a promising direction.
+\paragraph{Contextual agent security and policy enforcement.} Siu et al.~\cite{siu2026framework} formalize agent security as a contextual problem, defining task alignment, action alignment, source authorization, and data isolation as core properties. Policy-invisible violations fall within their action alignment dimension — specifically, cases where the policy-relevant state resides in organizational infrastructure rather than the agent's observation. PCAS~\cite{palumbo2026pcas} provides a general-purpose policy compiler with dependency graphs and reference monitors for deterministic enforcement; Sentinel is a narrower proof-of-concept focused on world-state-grounded verification rather than general policy compilation. Winston et al.~\cite{winston2026solver} use SMT solvers for runtime verification of tool call compliance; their approach verifies policies over agent-observable state, whereas our benchmark specifically isolates cases where the relevant state is absent from the agent's observation.
 
-\paragraph{Context-aware security.} Work on context-aware access control~\cite{contextaware} has explored incorporating situational context into authorization decisions. Our work applies similar principles to AI agent tool use, with organizational world-state as the context source.
+\paragraph{Privacy and policy benchmarks for agents.} PrivacyLens~\cite{shao2024privacylens} evaluates contextual privacy norm awareness in agent trajectories, confirming that model knowledge does not transfer to execution compliance — a finding our results extend to organizational policy. TOP-R~\cite{qiao2025topr} benchmarks aggregation leakage where agents combine tool outputs to infer sensitive information; this corresponds to our accumulated session leakage category, one of eight in PhantomPol-100. AgentLeak~\cite{elyagoubi2026agentleak} demonstrates that output-only auditing misses privacy violations in multi-agent internal channels, supporting our argument for tool-call-level interception. AgentDAM~\cite{agentdam2025} evaluates data minimization for autonomous web agents; our work addresses a complementary dimension — policy legality rather than data necessity. Keep Security!~\cite{chang2025keepsecurity} and Doc-PP~\cite{jang2026docpp} test policy preservation when policies are explicitly provided in context (visible-policy preservation). Our setting is complementary: we assume policy-relevant state is \emph{not} in the model's context, making the violation invisible to model reasoning.
 
 %% ============================================================
 \section{Conclusion}
 \label{sec:conclusion}
 %% ============================================================
 
-We have introduced policy-invisible violations as a distinct class of AI agent failures — actions that are user-sanctioned and model-appropriate but violate organizational policy because the relevant world state is absent from the model's execution context. We formalized a taxonomy of seven violation categories, released the PhantomPolicy benchmark of 20 cases with clean tool responses and a companion world model, and empirically demonstrated that four frontier models (GPT-4o, GPT-5.4, Claude Sonnet 4.6, Claude Opus 4.6) exhibit violation rates of 75--100\%.
+We have introduced policy-invisible violations as a distinct class of AI agent failures — actions that are user-sanctioned and model-appropriate but violate organizational policy because the relevant world state is absent from the model's execution context. We formalized a taxonomy of eight violation categories, released the PhantomPol-100 benchmark of 100 cases with clean tool responses and a companion world model, and empirically demonstrated that four frontier models (GPT-4o, GPT-5.4, Claude Sonnet 4.6, Claude Opus 4.6) exhibit violation rates of 75--100\%.
 
 The uniform failure of all four frontier models — ranging from 75\% to 100\% violation rates — illustrates the core problem: the capability that makes AI agents useful (faithful execution of user intent) is the same capability that makes policy-invisible violations likely. Reasoning capacity and policy compliance are orthogonal dimensions; stronger instruction-following does not confer stronger policy awareness.
 
